The '''in vivo bioreactor (IVB)''' is a [[regenerative medicine]] paradigm where bone is grown in vivo. The IVB has basic elements:
# Creation of a confined environment in vivo that is adjacent to a tissue locality rich in pluripotent cells,
# Injection of a Hydrogel Biomaterial with the appropriate physicochemical and biophysical characteristics in this confined environment so as to predictably alter the signaling environment or trigger a process within this confined environment leading to recapitulation of developmental processes and de novo formation of a functional tissue mass, and
# The harvest of the tissue from the confined site and transplantation of this tissue into another site within the patient, leading to a complete autologous tissue engineering strategy.

An example of the implementation of the IVB approach was in the engineering of autologous [[bone]] by injecting calcium [[alginate]] in a sub-periosteal location.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Stevens |first1=Molly M. |last2=Marini |first2=Robert P. |last3=Schaefer |first3=Dirk |last4=Aronson |first4=Joshua |last5=Langer |first5=Robert |last6=Shastri |first6=V. Prasad |title=In vivo engineering of organs: The bone bioreactor |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA |date=June 8, 2005 |volume=102 |issue=32 |pages=11450–11455 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0504705102 |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/102/32/11450.full#xref-ref-1-1 |accessdate=19 February 2014|pmc=1183576 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Service |first=Robert F. |title=Technique Uses Body as 'Bioreactor' to Grow New Bone |journal=Science |date=29 July 2005 |volume=309 |issue=5735 |pages=683 |doi=10.1126/science.309.5735.683a |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/309/5735/683.1.full |accessdate=19 February 2014 |pmid=16051759}}</ref>  The [[periosteum]] is a membrane that covers the long bones, jawbone, ribs and the skull. This membrane contains an endogenous population of pluripotent cells called the periosteal cells, which are a type of [[mesenchymal stem cells]] (MSC), which reside in the [[cambium]] layer, i.e., the side facing the bone. A key step in the procedure is the elevation of the periosteum without damaging the cambium surface and to ensure this a new technique called hydraulic elevation was developed.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Marini |first1=Robert P. |last2=Stevens |first2=Molly M. |last3=Langer |first3=Robert |last4=Shastri |first4=V. Prasad |title=Hydraulic Elevation of the Periosteum: A Novel Technique for Periosteal Harvest |journal=Journal of Investigative Surgery |year=2004 |volume=17 |issue=4 |pages=229–233 |doi=10.1080/08941930490472073 |url=http://informahealthcare.com/doi/abs/10.1080/08941930490472073 |accessdate=19 February 2014}}</ref>

The choice of the sub-periosteum site is used because stimulation of the cambium layer using transforming growth factor–beta resulted in enhanced [[chondrogenesis]], i.e., formation of [[cartilage]]. In development the formation of bone can either occur via a Cartilage template initially formed by the MSCs that then gets ossified through a process called [[endochondral ossification]] or directly from MSC [[Cellular differentiation|differentiation]] to bone via a process termed ''[[Intramembranous ossification|intra-membranous ossification]]''.  Upon exposure of the periosteal cells to calcium from the alginate gel, these cells become bone cells and start producing bone matrix through the intra-membranous ossification process, recapitulating all steps of bone matrix deposition.  The extension of the IVB paradigm to engineering autologous [[hyaline]] cartilage was also recently demonstrated.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Emans |first1=Pieter J. |author2=Lodewijk W. van Rhijn |author3=Welting, Tim J. M. |author4=Cremers, Andy |author5=Wijnands, Nina |author6=Spaapen, Frank |author7=J. Voncken, Willem |author8=Shastri, V. Prasad |title=Autologous engineering of cartilage |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA |date=January 7, 2010 |volume=107 |issue=8 |pages=3418–3423 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0907774107 |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/107/8/3418.abstract |accessdate=19 February 2014|pmc=2840469 }}</ref>  In this case, [[agarose]] is injected and this triggers local [[Agarose|hypoxia]], which then results in the differentiation of the periosteal MSCs into articular chondrocytes, i.e. cells similar to those found in the joint cartilage. Since this processes occurs in a relative short period of less than two weeks and cartilage can remodel into bone, this approach might provide some advantages in treatment of both cartilage and bone loss. The IVB concept needs to be however realized in humans and this is currently being undertaken.

